# Linting Workflow

After any substantive edit to a `.js`, `.jsx`, `.ts`, or `.tsx` file:

1. Run `npm run lint:fix` in the relevant project directory (`mobile-app/` or `backend/`) — runs `oxlint --fix --fix-suggestions --fix-dangerously` to auto-fix what it can
2. Use `ReadLints` on edited files to catch anything the linter can't auto-fix
3. Fix remaining errors manually
4. Never leave a task marked complete with outstanding lint errors

# No Conditional Spread

Never use `...(condition && { key: value })` to build objects conditionally. It is hard to read and obscures intent.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD
await updateDoc(conversationRef, {
  ...(data.groupName !== undefined && { groupName: data.groupName }),
  ...(data.groupImageURL !== undefined && { groupImageURL: data.groupImageURL }),
});

// ✅ GOOD
const updates = {};
if (data.groupName !== undefined) updates.groupName = data.groupName;
if (data.groupImageURL !== undefined) updates.groupImageURL = data.groupImageURL;
await updateDoc(conversationRef, updates);
```

# Type Imports (TypeScript files only)

Always use `import type` for type-only imports. Enforced by `@typescript-eslint/consistent-type-imports`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
import { MessageVectorMetadata } from "@/lib/rag-types";

// ✅ GOOD
import type { MessageVectorMetadata } from "@/lib/rag-types";
```

# No Inline `any` Casts Against Firebase Admin Results

Firebase Admin SDK query results are typed as `any`. Do not leave them untyped in production code — define an interface or use `as` narrowing explicitly.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — message is silently any
const messages = snapshot.docs.map((doc: any) => ({ messageId: doc.id, ...doc.data() }));

// ✅ GOOD — shape is explicit
interface FirestoreMessage {
  messageId: string;
  senderId: string;
  senderUsername: string;
  text: string;
  timestamp: FirebaseFirestore.Timestamp;
}
const messages: FirestoreMessage[] = snapshot.docs.map((doc) => ({
  messageId: doc.id,
  ...(doc.data() as Omit<FirestoreMessage, "messageId">),
}));
```
